2) Contacts & Relationship Graph (VERY IMPORTANT)
Use a unified Contact model with subtype profiles:
- Contact { id, kind: PERSON|ORGANIZATION, display_name, primary_email, primary_phone, tags[] }
- PersonProfile { contact_id, first_name, last_name, bar_number?, license_jurisdiction?, title? }
- OrganizationProfile { contact_id, legal_name, dba?, website? }
- ContactMethod { contact_id, type: EMAIL|PHONE|ADDRESS|SOCIAL, value, is_primary }
- ContactRelationship { from_contact_id, to_contact_id, relationship_type, notes } (e.g., employee-of, insured-by, spouse-of)

3) Matters / Cases
- Matter { id, organization_id, matter_number, name, practice_area, jurisdiction, venue, stage_id, status, opened_at, closed_at }
- MatterStage (configurable pipelines by practice_area)
- MatterType (configurable)
- MatterParticipant (THE KEY TABLE):
  - matter_id, contact_id
  - participant_role (configurable role definition, not hard-coded enums)
  - side: CLIENT_SIDE | OPPOSING_SIDE | NEUTRAL | COURT (nullable)
  - is_primary (bool)
  - represented_by_contact_id (nullable)  // link a party to their counsel contact
  - law_firm_contact_id (nullable)        // for counsel
  - notes
This MUST support: opposing counsel, opposing party, co-counsel, local counsel, adjuster, insurer, mediator/arbitrator, judge/court staff, expert, inspector, process server, lien claimant, witnesses, subcontractors, suppliers.

- MatterRelationship (optional): link related matters (e.g., parallel lien action)

